Animation

Summary

Name Documentation
tFrame
CAnimation

Description: CAnimation is an animation holder and player. It contains an integer to access the texture file with the animations. It also contains integers for the width and height of frames as well as for the position of the initial frame, the current frame and the total number of frames. It also contains a float for the framerate and a bool to tell if the animation will update to the next frame or not. Every character, enemy, or any object that will be animated, will have one or more CAnimations, and these will be updated and rendered depending on the state of each character, enemy or object.

        Stipulations: Every animated object will hold one or more CAnimations. Every CAnimation will play only the animation assigned to it. The CAnimation must be created and initialized upon creation of the owner object, and will be destroyed when the owner is destroyed.

        Interface: Every CAnimation will give its owner the power to initiate playback, pause it, reset it, stop (which is pausing and resetting). The owner must also make sure to update the animation and to render it as well.

Bitmap Font

Summary

Name Documentation
CLetter
CBMPFont

Description: CBMPFont will be a class owned by any other class that will need to display text, such as the HUD or menus. Every CBMPFont will have an int for its image ID, two ints for the height and width of the letters.

Stipulations: This class will be used to render text to the screen without using default fonts, and this way it will help create and maintain an ambient for the game.

Interface: The CBMPFont will only have functionality to be set up and to receive a string of text and render it.

CGame

CGame

 

Description:

        This class contains all of the information for the game to run. It is a singleton.

 

Stipulations:

        This class will be initialized in the entire program's main method.

 

Interface:

        This class controls all of the different states which control what happens in the game.

Class Diagram
GameAudio

Summary

Name Documentation
CAudioFile

Description: AudioFile is a singleton class that will have an int for the sound ID, and an int for the type of audio. It works with an ENUM that will contain the following types: MUSIC, FX, DIALOGUE.

Stipulations: This class will be used by the CAudioMaster in order to keep control of the sounds and volumes.

Interface: This class will feature mutators and accessors, as well as a setup function.

CAudioMaster

Description: AudioMaster is a singleton class that will have an int for the number of sounds, an array of CAudioFiles for every single piece of audio in the game. It will also have ints for the audio levels of the music, FX, and dialogue. It will also allow for volume changes.

Stipulations: This class will be used to load sound files, save and load sound settings and keep coherent levels between different audio files.

Interface: The CAudioMaster will load all the audio files in the game. It will have controls for changing the volume; this will change the volume levels of the correspondent audio files.  It will also load and save volume settings automatically. And it will provide the game with access to the sound IDs as well as allowing them to play, pause, stop and reset playback.

Class Diagram
HUD

Summary

Name Documentation
CHUD

Description: CHUD will display important gameplay information such as player character portraits, healthbars, it will provide access to the menu from the main gameplay state as well as access to the inventory. It will present information to the user that wouldn’t be otherwise available from the game itself. It will have two ints for the ID to the background image and marker image and it will also have an array of four ints, one for each player character’s health. It will have a string for the dialogue as well as an instance to a bitmap font. It will also contain instances of the mini-map and inventory classes.

Stipulations: This class will be used to provide feedback and an advanced measure of control to the player.

Interface: The CHUD will interact with menu states, it will also interact with player characters, inventory, items within the inventory, special feats and abilities and it will provide the player with a mini map.  It will be set up, updated and rendered by the main gameplay state.

Managers

Summary

Name Documentation
CCollisionManager CCollisionManager

 

Description:

        The Collision Manager will be filled with objects from the Object Manager as they are added to the Object Manager. Every frame the Collision Manager will run the collisions based on the type of the object.

 

Stipulations:

        CBase objects will be stored in the Collision Manager in order to run different types of collisions on each object.

CObjectManager CObjectManager

 

Description:

        The Object Manager will hold every object created in the game and calls the render and update on them every frame.

 

Stipulations:

        Objects will need to be added to this class for it to know what the items are, at which point, unless another pointer is set up, the Object Manager will be the only one that knows about the objects.

 

Interface:

        This module will call the render and update functions of all CBase objects registered with it.

CCamera

CCamera : public CBase

 

Description:

        This provides an object through which the Object Manager can position the object based on what the camera should be viewing. Objects will be conditioned out based on whether the camera is the main camera or the mini map and scaled based on that also.

 

Stipulations:

        The Object Manager will use the cameras to know where to draw certain objects. Once a camera is initialized to a position and scale, an object will be passed to it if it should be drawn in that view. The camera will render it accordingly.

 

Interface:

        This module will call the render functions of CBase objects.

Class Diagram
Particle Engine

Summary

Name Documentation
CParticle

Description: CParticle is the class that will be created and used by the Particle Engine to create the particle effects on screen. Every particle will have an int serving as the image ID, an int for the life, which is a countdown for the time that it will take from the moment it is created to the moment when it is due to be destroyed, ints for height and width, as well as floats for X and Y coordinates (position).

Stipulations: Every particle will be owned by a particle engine instance. This instance will create, update, render and destroy every particle it owns.

Interface: The particle can only be created/initialized, updated, displayed and destroyed, and only by the particle engine that owns it.

CParticleEmitter

Description: CParticleEngine is a class that will hold one or more CParticles in order to have them displayed on-screen. It will have an int for the image ID for the particles, two ints for the height and width of the particle image, two floats for positions X and Y, and it will have an array of particles.

Stipulations: Every particle engine will own one or more particles. It will initialize, update and display them.

Interface: The particle engine will have initialize, update and render functions, from which it will call the respective functions for every particle.

Name Documentation
CMainMenuState

CMainMenuState : public IGameState

 

Description:

        This state is activated when the game is started or re-started and contains all of the different functions of a main menu. It is a singleton.

 

Stipulations:

        This state will be activated when the game is started or when an option is chosen to go back to the main menu.

 

Interface:

        This state has all of the options that will be on the main menu.

CPauseMenuState

CPauseMenuState : public IGameState

 

Description:

        This state is activated when the game is paused and gives pause menu options. It is a singleton.

 

Stipulations:

        This state will be activated when CGamePlayState detects that the player has paused the game.

 

Interface:

        This state has all of the options that will be on the pause menu.

IGameState

IGameState

 

Description:

        This is the abstract base class for game states. It contains virtual Enter, Exit, Input, Update, and Render functions which must be overridden in the child classes.

 

Stipulations:

        All of the game states will be derived from this.

CGamePlayState

CGamePlayState : public IGameState

 

Description:

        This state is activated when the game is entered through the main menu, or when leaving the pause menu to resume the game. It is a singleton.

 

Stipulations:

        This state will be activated when an option is chosen on the main menu or pause menu to start or resume the game.

 

Interface:

        This state contains all of the gameplay elements for the entire game.

CGameData

Description: CGameData will be storage for the player status in the game. It will hold current scores, current level, game progress, items etc. It is this class that will be saved and loaded from the menu. The GameData class will have an array of four player characters, it will contain an inventory, and ints for the level and score.

Stipulations: The GameData will be updated when the player completes a level or when the player decides to save the game.

Interface: The GameData class will have a function for updating and for returning values for the data it contains. It will also contain the functionality to save the data to a file, and load data from a file.

        This state is activated when the game is entered through the main menu, or when leaving the pause menu to resume the game. It is a singleton.

 

Stipulations:

        This state will be activated when an option is chosen on the main menu or pause menu to start or resume the game.

 

Interface:

        This state contains all of the gameplay elements for the entire game.

Documentation

Description: CGameData will be storage for the player status in the game. It will hold current scores, current level, game progress, items etc. It is this class that will be saved and loaded from the menu. The GameData class will have an array of four player characters, it will contain an inventory, and ints for the level and score.

Stipulations: The GameData will be updated when the player completes a level or when the player decides to save the game.

Interface: The GameData class will have a function for updating and for returning values for the data it contains. It will also contain the functionality to save the data to a file, and load data from a file.
